d argue it would be more advantageous to view microenterprise as a social and economic development strategy rather than simply as an anti-poverty strategy. Based on this observation, a range of strategies to better promote microenterprise programs among the poor is advanced, with the goal of targeting the most promising approaches.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEntrepreneurshipzUnited States. 0aPoorxEmploymentzUnited States. 0aSelf-employedzUnited States. 0aSmall businesszUnited States. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 4aSociology : Social Problems. 4aSociology : Urban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aSanders, Cynthia K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSherraden, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSsewamala, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791484661423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791484661/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles